<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chineseremaindertheorem" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Chinese Remainder Theorem</title>

  <p>
    Another topic that is important is simultaneously solving systems of linear equations across multiple moduli.
    In other words, we can consider linear equations with a single variable, but where each linear equation uses a different value for <m>n</m>.
    Let's look at an example.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider the following two equations:
    <md>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 1 \bmod 5</mrow>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 4 \bmod 7</mrow>
    </md>
    We can ask the question: is there a solution to this system of equations?
    In this case, we see that <m>x=11</m> is a solution, since <m>11\equiv 1 \bmod 5</m> and <m>11\equiv 4 \bmod 7</m>.
    What this means is that the number <m>11</m> plays two roles simultaneously: we have <m>[11]=[1]</m> in <m>\mathbb{Z}/5\mathbb{Z}</m> and <m>[11]=[4]</m> in <m>\mathbb{Z}/7\mathbb{Z}</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider the following more complicated example:
    <md>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 12 \bmod 17</mrow>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 14 \bmod 23</mrow>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 3 \bmod 29</mrow>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 97 \bmod 103</mrow>
    </md>
    In this case, we have that <m>x=206715</m> is a solution.
    Again, what does this mean? It means that the number <m>206715</m> plays four roles simultaneously: we have <m>[206715]=[12]</m> in <m>\mathbb{Z}/17\mathbb{Z}</m>, <m>[206715]=[14]</m> in <m>\mathbb{Z}/23\mathbb{Z}</m>, <m>[206715]=[3]</m> in <m>\mathbb{Z}/29\mathbb{Z}</m>, and <m>[206715]=[97]</m> in <m>\mathbb{Z}/103\mathbb{Z}</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    This leads to the following problem: given <m>a_1,\ldots,a_k</m> and <m>n_1,\ldots,n_k</m>, can we find a number <m>x</m> such that <m>[x]=[a_i]</m> in <m>\mathbb{Z}/n_i\mathbb{Z}</m> for each <m>i=1,\ldots,k</m>?
  </p>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Discuss these examples and this question. Do they make sense? Why or why not?
    </p>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    The answer to this question is known as the Chinese Remainder Theorem, because problems of this type were solved 1500 years ago by mathematicians in China.
  </p>
  
  <theorem xml:id="thm-chineseremaindertheorem">
    <title>Chinese Remainder Theorem</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>n_1,\ldots,n_k</m> are pairwise coprime, i.e., that <m>\gcd(n_i,n_j)=1</m> for all <m>i\neq j</m>.
        Then for any choice of <m>a_i\in \{0,1,\ldots,n_i-1\}</m>, the system of equations given by 
        <md>
          <mrow>x \amp \equiv a_1 \bmod n_1</mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp \equiv a_2 \bmod n_2</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp \vdots </mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp \equiv a_k \bmod n_k</mrow>
        </md>
        has a unique solution in <m>\{0,1,2,\ldots,n_1n_2\cdots n_k-1\}</m>.
        In other words, there is a unique congruence class <m>x\in \mathbb{Z}/n_1n_2\cdots n_k \mathbb{Z}</m> whose representatives simultaneously solve these equations.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            With your group, create one example of a system of equations where this theorem applies, and create one example of a system where this theorem does not apply.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Create an example of a system of equations where this theorem does not apply, but where there is a solution.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </exercise>

  <proof>
    <p>
      We first prove that if a solution exists, then it is unique.
      Suppose that <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are both solutions to the above system of equations.
      This means that for each <m>i</m>, we have
      <md>
        x-y \equiv 0 \bmod n_i
      </md>
      and thus each <m>n_i</m> divides <m>x-y</m>.
      Since the <m>n_i</m> are pairwise coprime, this least common multiple is their product, and this must divide <m>x-y</m> as well.
      Thus, <m>[x]=[y]</m> in <m>x\in \mathbb{Z}/n_1n_2\cdots n_k \mathbb{Z}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      We next show how to construct a solution to this system of equations.
      We start with the case of two equations.
      Bezout's identity states that we can find <m>m_1</m> and <m>m_2</m> such that
      <md>
        n_1m_1+n_2m_2=1 \, .
      </md>
      We now claim that we have a solution to the first two equations given by 
      <md>
        x = a_1 m_2 n_2 + a_2 m_1 n_1 \, .
      </md>
      This is a solution because we can replace <m>m_2n_2 = 1-n_1m_1</m> in the above equation to get
      <md>
        x \equiv a_1 (1-n_1m_1) + a_2 n_1m_1
      </md>
      and when we reduce this modulo <m>n_1</m> we get <m>a_1</m>.
      A similar calculation shows that this holds for <m>a_2</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      When <m>k\geq 3</m>, we can use a similar process to the case of two equations.
      Specifically, let <m>N=n_1n_2\cdots n_k</m> and let <m>S_i=N/n_i</m>.
      Since the original <m>n_i</m> are coprime, we have that <m>\gcd(S_i,n_i)=1</m>.
      Thus, there is a multiplicative inverse of <m>[S_i]</m> in <m>\mathbb{Z}/n_i\mathbb{Z}</m>, which we will call <m>[R_i]=[S_i]^{-1}</m>.
      This multiplicative inverse can be found by solving the Bezout identity, as we have done previously.
      We define 
      <md>
        x = \sum_{i=1}^k a_iR_iS_i \, .
      </md>
        We know that <me>a_iR_iS_i \equiv a_i \bmod n_i</me> for each <m>i</m> due to the additive inverse relationship.
        We also have that if <m>i\neq j</m>, then 
        <md>
          n_i \mid S_j = n_1n_2\cdots n_k/n_j \, .
        </md>
        Thus, 
        <md>
          x\equiv a_i \bmod n_i 
        </md>
        for each <m>i</m>, as desired.
    </p>
  </proof>
  
  <exercise>
    <p>
      Discuss this proof with your group. Does it make sense? Why or why not?
    </p>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    Let's work through an example to solve such a system of equations.
    Suppose we have
    <md>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 1 \bmod 3</mrow>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 2 \bmod 5</mrow>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 4 \bmod 7</mrow>
    </md>
    Using the notation from the proof, we have that <m>N=3\cdot 5\cdot 7 = 105</m>, <m>S_1=35</m>, <m>S_2=21</m>, and <m>S_3=15</m>.
    Computing inverses, we have <m>[35]_3=[2]_3</m> (where the 3 subscript indicates the modulus) and since <m>[2]_3^{-1}=[2]_3</m>, we have <m>R_1=2</m>.
    Similarly, <m>[21]_5=[1]_5</m>, so <m>[1]_5^{-1}=[1]_5</m> and thus <m>R_2=1</m>.
    Finally, <m>[15]_7=[1]_7</m>, so <m>[1]_7^{-1}=[1]_7</m> and thus <m>R_3=1</m>.
    Putting this together, we have
    <md>
      <mrow>x \amp = a_1 S_1 R_1 + a_2 S_2 R_2 + a_2 S_2 R_2 </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = 1\cdot 35\cdot 2 + 2 \cdot 21\cdot 1 + 4 \cdot 15 \cdot 1</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp = 172</mrow>
    </md>
    If we reduce <m>172</m> modulo <m>105</m>, we obtain <m>67</m>.
    Thus, <m>67</m> is our unique solution in <m>\{0,1,2,\ldots, 104\}</m>.
  </p>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Find the solution to the following system of equations.
          <md>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 3 \bmod 5</mrow>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 1 \bmod 6</mrow>
      <mrow>x \amp \equiv 2 \bmod 11</mrow>
    </md>
    </p>
  </exercise>


  

</section>